What is the difference between terraform plan and terraform apply?
terraform plan: displays the blueprint of all the creations, deletions, modifications the terraform files are going to do
terraform apply: execute the blueprint

What is the state file and what happens if you delete it?
it keeps track of all the resources, providers, service accounts. if we delete it, it will recreate everything again when we apply again and cause several issues.
*If you delete the state file, Terraform loses track of what it already created. Running terraform apply again will try to create everything from scratch — but the resources already exist on GCP, causing conflicts and errors like 'resource already exists'. The state file is the source of truth between your config and real infrastructure.

What is the difference between a resource and a variable in Terraform?
resource is for creating the cloud resources like a bq asset, bucket, dataproc cluster, etc...
variable are like env variables. we can either assign default value or assign while applying the terraform

What is idempotency in Terraform — what does it mean practically?
running same config multiple time will change nothing as the desired state is already achieved. its like git. every change is incremental or decremental as per requirement. not replacing.

Why is force_destroy = true on the bucket important?
the terraform creates many resources as per the config. if we don't destroy, all resources will start charging credits.
*GCS buckets can't be deleted if they contain objects. Without force_destroy = true, terraform destroy will fail if the bucket has any files in it. force_destroy = true tells Terraform to delete all objects in the bucket before deleting the bucket itself.